<br>
   I've played evertything from Pinball, to Pong, to D&amp;D, to home consoles, to computer games.  For 27 years.  Non-stop.<br>
<br>
   I've heard the tired refrain of &quot;Johnny wouldn't have (insert horrible act here) if he hadn't played (insert game here)&quot; more times than I could count.<br>
<br>
   And with each one until this one, I answered with the same notion that nobody would commit (horrible act) if there weren't already messed up to begin with.<br>
<br>
   Admittedly this woman doesn't really have an idea what she's talking about, but she may have hit upon a nugget of truth.<br>
<br>
   First off, is Everquest addictive?  For the right person it is extremely addictive.  I have tried to quit 4 times now.  This last time I deleted every single character I ever made, cancelled the account, uninstalled the whole game then broke all the disks.  And as for play time, when my job moved sites, I never bothered looking for another, and lived on money in the bank.  40 hours a week is nothing.  40 hours a week would be my minimum in my heyday.  The average would be closer to 90 or 100 hours per week.<br>
<br>
   Can EQ lead to suicide?  I dunno, it might be a stretch, but it might be possible.  It depends on the person and how well they deal with the kind of stress EQ can generate.<br>
<br>
   If you are the kind of person that is sharing and tends to place a high emotional investment in people you're gonna get hurt.  Alot.  <br>
<br>
  So you have a game that sends you into downward emotional spirals that you cant quit.  Not a good combination.<br>
<br>
   There is something about the game (for me at least) that drove me to emotional reaction.  Nothing else did.  I had hardly ever cried in my life until I started EQ, then it was a once a month or once a week thing. <br>
<br>
My main character was a druid, and I'd often teleport people for free, get strangers to donate items then give the items away in a contest for newbies.  I just played for the social interaction.  Levelling bored me silly.<br>
<br>
   Here's just one example of the kind of person I'd encounter at least once a month:<br>
<br>
   I met this guy in Firiona Vie that asked how much for a port to West commons.  I was in a good mood, so I said &quot;Free&quot;.  He acted very gracious and happy about the whole thing and told me I was one of the few nice people on the server (Rallos Zek).  We got to talking and before very long we were talking about our real lives, we talked for about 3 hours straight.  For the next two nights in a row I kept bumping into him and each time we talked for about three hours.  9 hours was more than I'd spent talking to anyone else on planet earth that week, in game or out.<br>
<br>
   On the fourth night he sends me a tell asking for a port from West Commons to Eastern Karana.  I said &quot;sorry man, I can't this time&quot;.  He begged me for about 2 solid minutes.  Then I politely informed that I was already waiting almost 15 minutes for the boat to arrive so I could go help a guildmate in ocean of tears, and me running from WC back to docks wouldn't take me much less than it would for him to make the run to EK (only 2 zones away) and I would probably end up waitin another 15 minutes for the boat.  He fell silent for about 3 minutes then sent a tell saying &quot;you louser mother f'ing piece of $h!t etc.&quot;  He cussed me out like I've never been cussed out before.<br>
<br>
   I just camped right there and cried for about 20 minutes.<br>
<br>
   I could fill pages with stories like that one.<br>
<br>
   The bottom line is that it's still true that someone has to have a screw loose to kill themselves over EQ, But the game goes to levels unseen by any game before (computer or otherwise) to sending people into states of depression or emotional breakdown.<br>
<br>
   My 2 cents.<br>
<br>
   - Iscin<br>
