<br>
I write games as a hobby---it will eventually be a career. Every time I come up with a game idea, I have to ask myself if this idea is going to get me into trouble. I've seen so many game ideas die in utero because of crap like this. My latest project, which has been suspended since Sept. 11, was a game where you drove around a city, blowing up empty buildings with heavily armed hatchbacks, twisted metal style. The demos I made for the game were fun to play,print magazines were very interested, and it looked like I might finally get something published after 3 years of trying and failing. Post Sept. 11, a publisher wouldn't touch my game with a ten foot cattle prod. In this case, a good game is going to waste because of current events. It happens sometimes. But, can you imagine the protests that would happen if I released that game?<br>
<br>
On the other side of the spectrum is EQ. This has to be one of the most benign games on the market. If a massively popular game has one death attributed to it out of 400,000 players, you have to think that this guy was just a little off-center to begin with. Besides, it's all a numbers game. What are the statistical chances that a young person who likes to play PC games will own at least one iteration of the following games:<br>
<br>
The Sims<br>
Quake/Doom<br>
EQ/Ultima Online<br>
<br>
Pretty high. So, if that person kills himself, how do you determine that his suicide is related to a video game, and not a million other possibilities. In this guy's case, EQ was probably the best thing going for him. Do you think he might be trying to escape an overly controlling family, or a career choice that was a deadend, etc? Or, do you think the demons of EQ infected his soul and told him to eat a bullet?<br>
<br>
